We use the central limit formulas for a random total. \[\mu_{\sum{X}} ~=~ n\cdot\mu_{X} ~=~ (34)(72.39) ~=~ 2461.26 \] \[\sigma_{\sum{X}} = \sigma_{X}\sqrt{n} = (9.58)\sqrt{34} = 55.8605192\] So, we think the random total is normally distributed with a mean of 2461.26 and a standard deviation of 55.8605192. \[\sum{X} \sim N(2461.26,\,55.8605192) \]

Calculate a \(z\)-score for the boundary. \[z = \frac{2510-2461.26}{55.8605192} = 0.8725304 \]

You can round that to \(z=0.87\) or \(z=0.88\). Any of the following probabilities will get credit. \[P(Z > 0.8725304) = 0.1914596 \] \[P(Z > 0.87) = 0.1922 \] \[P(Z > 0.88) = 0.1894 \]
